Let me examine the test method more carefully and also check what error could be occurring. Looking at the test, it seems to be related to the issue with default implementation handling. The problem might be in how `SimpleType` handles equality checks when dealing with different `defaultImpl` configurations. Let me look more carefully at the `equals` method in `SimpleType.java`:

Looking at the `equals` method:

```java
@Override
public boolean equals(Object o)
{
    if (o == this) return true;
    if (o == null) return false;
    if (o.getClass() != getClass()) return false;

    SimpleType other = (SimpleType) o;

    // Classes must be identical...
    if (other._class != this._class) return false;

    // And finally, generic bindings, if any
    TypeBindings b1 = _bindings;
    TypeBindings b2 = other._bindings;
    return b1.equals(b2);
}
```

The issue seems to be that the `equals` method in `SimpleType` does not consider the handlers (`_valueHandler`, `_typeHandler`) and the `_asStatic` flag when checking equality. In the context of subtype handling with `defaultImpl`, this can cause problems because different type instances with different handlers might be considered equal when they shouldn't be.

Let me also check the parent class `TypeBase` to understand the full picture:

